“Our sea”: landlocked Bolivia hopes that the court will reopen its way to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors patrol the naval headquarters in La Paz.
Blue flags are displayed on public buildings.
Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are painted with the slogan: “The sea is ours by right.
“Giving it back is our duty.”
Across landlocked Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile as a result of a bloody 19th-century conflict over resources is still alive; alive and striving to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
Those hopes may have been the boldest in decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of the international court, which will take place on 1 October as a result of five years of debate.
“Bolivia has the energy, the spirit of unity and the mental balance and, of course, they are waiting for a positive result,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will watch the International Court of Justice ruling on big screens across the country, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will be able to support Bolivia's claim that, after decades of tense negotiations, Chile is obliged to negotiate a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president who is waging a difficult battle for re-election next year, is also eagerly awaiting a decision on Monday.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to make a decision in favor of Bolivia, and if it does, that will change little.
The UN body in the Netherlands has no authority to control Chilean territory and has already said that it will have no influence on the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the ruling of the International Court of Justice was delivered only six months after the last arguments were heard suggests that the case “was not complicated,” says Pas Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
For the past four years, the Bolivian case has not progressed, but, on the contrary, it has been postponed all the time.
“The current Bolivian administration has used the problem of access to the sea for criminal purposes,” Zarate said.
According to her, Morales’ bellicose rhetoric has destroyed Chile’s last benevolence.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss afterwards.
The two countries have not had diplomatic relations since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Velce, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, disagrees that the court’s decision was made too quickly.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an exceptional opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “put an end to 139 years of mutually beneficial disagreements,” he argues.
Calzadilla also disagrees that Morales, still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, uses the naval issue as a political trump card.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“The court’s decision is an opportunity to reassure us that we need to step over our past.”
