John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance for the citizens of the world
Scottish independent schools continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was once again confirmed in 2018: outstanding exam results demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other socially significant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 students are enrolled throughout Scotland, and where they strive to provide the highest level of service for students and their parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen careers, as well as for the status of world citizens.
As part of the education sector, which is responsible for the design and implementation of individual school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you call on his mind.
If you speak to him in his native tongue, you turn to his heart.”
This is convincing evidence that we cannot rely solely on the English language if we want to build relationships with citizens of other countries and be able to trust them.
According to the results of the last exams of this year, we see that the languages occupy a leading position in the league tables and have the highest score on the results of exams in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of pupils who studied foreign languages received the highest grade “A”.
Data obtained from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of pupils received an “A” in Mandarin (Chinese dialect), while 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also received an “A”.
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Currently, language subjects are in the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that among the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill job vacancies, 17 percent were due to a lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are needed in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will gain a real advantage by mastering another additional skill that will be useful to him throughout his later life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage – it was spoken by 15 percent of respondents.
That’s why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowing several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In schools in Scotland, there is quite a wide variety in terms of the languages that are taught - each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in light of the country’s future development until 2020 – such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with a teaching staff whose members are experts in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages continue to be vital for the future development of the country, so this should be reflected appropriately in education.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits to Scotland’s youth.
It's going to be fair.
John Edwards, Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
