North Korea says it will not "categorically" disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued sanctions increase distrust of the United States and that his country will not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under any circumstances.
Ri Yong-ho said at the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial goodwill measures” last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and committing not to build up nuclear weapons stockpiles or develop nuclear technology.
"But we are not seeing a symmetrical reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be able to unilaterally take disarmament action first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for step-by-step steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not reject unilateral unchecked denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ree cited a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent U.S. president and the North Korean leader, which took place in Singapore on June 12; then Kim promised to start a move towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” and Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea seeks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that ‘denuclearization must be done first,’ and is raising the level of pressure through sanctions to enforce its goal and even object to ‘declaration of war to end,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a utopian dream of people who don’t know us.
But the real problem is that the ongoing sanctions are increasing our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, and added: “If South Korea, rather than the United States, had been a party to this denuclearization issue, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have been so deadlocked.”
However, Ri’s tone of speech differed sharply from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s missile targeting of the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “suicide missile.”
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his boldness in taking disarmament measures, but said there was more to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea disarms.
