Harvard students learn to rest on special courses
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, has helped all elementary students learn to sleep more and fight the chauvinistic culture of continuous caffeine intake with the goal of staying awake all night.
One academic found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaysler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he was enthralled by the idea of introducing such a course, having previously made a report on the impact of lack of sleep on learning processes.
“At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘I’m so sorry I only found out about it now that I’m almost done.’
She said that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, tells how a healthy sleep habit promotes academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves a person’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s Health Service, says the university decided to introduce this course after it was found that students experienced a severe lack of sleep during the school week.
The class lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
One section of the class offers a picture of a dorm room where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, simulators and books, get information about how each of these activities and substances - coffee, light, which cause lack of sleep - affect athletic performance, and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants will learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
An interactive campus map encourages course participants to reflect on their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just like any other person has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects their health,” added Professor Cheysler.
According to him, the false sense of pride that a person can “sniff all night” is still quite common, and modern technology, as well as increasing pressure on students, mean that sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
According to him, a sufficient amount of good quality sleep is a “secret weapon” of the student to fight stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to fight excess weight, since lack of sleep puts the brain in fasting mode, causing him to constantly experience a feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheysler design the course by attending one of the classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread this information throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar curriculum before enrolling in a competitive educational institution.
Professor Chaysler recommends that students set an alarm clock to warn them to go to bed and wake up, as well as to remember about the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps, which disrupts a person’s biorhythm and leads to problems falling asleep.
