Almanach: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now the page of our almanac "Sunday morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago on this day in Germany was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity — an invention that eventually led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
Becoming one of the foundations of science, Geiger's counter has also become one of the foundations of popular culture, and this is reflected in the 1950s film "The Coronado Bell", with the cowboys Roy Rogers and Dale Evans - such seemingly unlike scientists - in the lead roles:
Man: "What kind of thing is this?"
Rogers: “This is a Geiger counter, used to detect radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can really hear the effects of atoms generated by radioactivity in minerals.”
Evans: "That's right, I can hear it now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, not even a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But his invention, named after his author, is still widely used.
