The Festival of World Citizens, which opened in 2012, is a continuation of the global project to combat poverty, which is being carried out by an international group of human rights defenders hoping to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To get a free ticket to the event (unless you’re willing to pay for a VIP ticket), you had to volunteer or email a world leader, make a phone call, or perform any other or other meaningful action to help raise awareness of your goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has the Festival of World Citizens become in 12 years in terms of achieving its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with free attendance to a concert really convincing fellow citizens to demand a call to action, or is it just another case of so-called “clictivism” where people believe they are making real changes by signing an online petition or tweeting?
The organizers of Global Citizen say that since 2011, the festival has registered more than 19 million “actions” held by its supporters, which pursue many different goals.
It is mentioned that through these actions, world leaders have pledged to provide funds worth more than $37 billion, which should affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group voiced 390 commitments and announcements that were made as a result of its actions, at least $10 billion of which had already been paid or raised.
The group estimates that the funds provided direct assistance to nearly 649 million people around the world.
One of the most significant commitments is called The Power of Nutrition: a British partnership of investors and implementation professionals committed to “helping children reach their full potential” pledged to provide $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the district. This was done after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens members.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can make social injustice against malnutrition a thing of the past,” said Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracy Ullman during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions were taken urging the UK to improve nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced funding for the Power of Nutrition project, which will reach 5 million women and children through activities designed to improve nutrition.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the festival’s website: “Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?”
The organizers of Global Citizen respond: “It will be a long and difficult road on which we will trip and fall from time to time.
But as in the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements, we will succeed because together we are stronger.
