National Trust listens to the secret lives of bats
A new study, conducted in one of the Scottish Highlands estates, aims to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is hoped that the findings will give a new look at the behaviour of unique winged mammals and will help in further conservation efforts.
The study, organized by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland, will study common bats, soprano bats, as well as brown long-haired bats and Dobanton nightshades inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile field surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
A map of the habitat will then be compiled and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Conservation Adviser, hopes these findings will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the main directions of habitat management, such as the formation of meadows, as well as ways to maintain forests in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened with extinction due to construction and development works that affect their habitat and loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can be dangerous, as can fly adhesive tape, chemical treatment of building materials and hunting domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to accurately identify obstacles on the flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat populations very seriously.
The organization employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, on-the-spot checks, and sometimes rescue work.
The organization even created Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Thrave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of Scottish bats live.
Property manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect area for them.
“Here at Threave, it’s a great place for bats,” he says.
“There are old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the elements of a good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need for a prosperous existence.”
He recalls the importance of checking for bats before conducting maintenance within private holdings, since the unintentional destruction of one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and perhaps even to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer at the Bat Conservation Foundation, is calling on the public for help.
She says, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how many of their individual species live.”
