How a Trade War with America Could Benefit Beijing
Experts believe the first salvos of the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and while the battle is far from over, the split between the two countries could benefit Beijing in the long run.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued his first warning earlier this year by taxing major Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, when new tariffs affected $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) in goods, effectively taxing half of all U.S. goods coming from China.
Beijing has struck back every time, recently imposing $60 billion in tariffs on U.S. goods ranging from five to ten percent.
China has promised that retaliatory measures against the United States will be equivalent every time, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to start experiencing even the slightest difficulties in the near future.
To force Washington to back down means to yield to the demands, but to publicly yield to the US would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
However, experts believe that if Beijing can play its cards correctly, the pressure of the US trade war could provide long-term support for China, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a premature political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that would lead to an economic spin-off in either of these countries is actually much more dangerous than previously acknowledged by observers,” said Abigail Grace, a research fellow at the Center for New American Security, which specializes in Asia.
Syrian Foreign Minister Says ‘Ready’ to Return Refugees
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild a country that has been devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
Speaking at the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country are improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground has become more stable and safer thanks to the successes in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rebuild the areas destroyed by terrorists so that people can live there in peace.
All conditions are now in place for refugees to return voluntarily to the country they had to leave because of terrorist attacks and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be grateful for help in rebuilding the destroyed country.
But he stressed that the country will not accept aid on any terms or assistance from countries sponsoring terrorism.
