Red tide: news The concentration of microorganisms decreased in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota
The Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission’s latest report reflects an overall decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay Area.
According to FWC, in the areas of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties reported abundant flowering, which indicates a decrease in the concentration of microorganisms.
The Red Tide stretches approximately 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinells to the southern Lee counties.
Foci can be seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but their number has decreased significantly compared to last week.
A red tide is also observed in Pascoe County.
Last week, average concentrations were reported in and near Pinellas County, low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County's coastal area, high concentrations in Manati and Sarasota County and coastal areas, average concentrations in Charlotte County, high concentrations on the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Cole County.
In Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, airway irritation is still likely.
In Northwest Florida, no such possibility was reported last week.
